et: Middle English {it}ook, oke,{/it} going back to Old English{it} āc,{/it} going back to Germanic {it}*eik-{/it} (whence also Old Frisian {it}ēk{/it} "oak," Old Saxon {it}ēc,{/it} Old High German {it}eih, eihha,{/it} Old Norse {it}eik{/it}), of obscure origin

Old English {it}āc{/it} is a feminine root noun (dative singular and nominative plural {it}ǣc{/it}), though forms leveled to other declensions with umlaut are already evident. Germanic {it}*eik-{/it} has been compared with the Greek words {it}aigílōps,{/it} a name in Theophrastus for a species of oak ({it}Quercus macrolepis{/it}?), and {it}krátaigos,{/it} a species of hawthorn (also in Theophrastus), but interpretation of the conjoined elements of these words is conjectural ({it}lṓpē{/it} is not actually attested in the sense "cork" or "bark"). The derivation of Latin {it}aesculus{/it} "a species of oak ({it}Quercus petraea{/it}?)" is obscure. The Lithuanian dialect forms {it}áižuols{/it} and {it}áužuolas{/it} "oak," superficially comparable, are hypercorrections of {it}ą́žuolas,{/it} which is very unlikely to be related to {it}*eik-{/it} (cf. Old Prussian {it}ansonis{/it} = German {it}eche{/it} in the {it}Elbing Vocabulary{/it}).
